    <!-- S1: WHAT IS NODE.JS -->
    <div class="section open" id="s1">
      <div class="section-head" onclick="toggle('s1')">
        <div class="section-num">01</div>
        <div class="section-title">What is Node.js?</div>
        <div class="section-chevron">▼</div>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h2>What is Node.js?</h2>
        <p>Node.js is a <strong>JavaScript runtime environment</strong> that allows you to run JavaScript <em>outside the browser</em> — on a server, on your laptop, anywhere.</p>
        <p>Before Node.js, JavaScript only worked inside web browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari). You could make websites interactive, but you <strong>could not build a backend server</strong> with JavaScript. Node.js changed that completely.</p>

        <div class="callout success">
          <div class="callout-icon">💡</div>
          <div class="callout-text"><strong>Simple definition:</strong> Node.js lets you write backend code (servers, APIs, databases) using the same JavaScript you already know from the browser.</div>
        </div>

        <h3>Quick History</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>2009</strong> — Ryan Dahl created Node.js at Joyent</li>
          <li><strong>Problem:</strong> Web servers in 2009 were slow at handling multiple simultaneous connections</li>
          <li><strong>Idea:</strong> Take Google's V8 JavaScript engine (very fast!) and let it run on the server</li>
          <li><strong>Result:</strong> A fast, scalable, non-blocking server runtime</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="diagram">
          <div class="node green">JavaScript (your code)</div>
          <div class="arrow">↓</div>
          <div class="node yellow">Chrome V8 Engine (compiler)</div>
          <div class="arrow">↓</div>
          <div class="node purple">Node.js Runtime (the environment)</div>
          <div class="arrow">↓</div>
          <div class="node cyan">Backend Applications, APIs, Servers</div>
        </div>

        <div class="analogy">
          <div class="analogy-title">🍕 Real-Life Analogy — Restaurant</div>
          <div class="analogy-body">
            Think of Node.js like a restaurant kitchen. <br>
            <strong>JavaScript</strong> = the recipe (your code)<br>
            <strong>V8 Engine</strong> = the chef who reads and cooks the recipe<br>
            <strong>Node.js Runtime</strong> = the full kitchen with all tools, appliances, and systems<br>
            <strong>Your App</strong> = the finished meal served to customers
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- S2: WHY NODE.JS WAS CREATED -->
    <div class="section open" id="s2">
      <div class="section-head" onclick="toggle('s2')">
        <div class="section-num">02</div>
        <div class="section-title">Why Node.js Was Created — The Problem It Solved</div>
        <div class="section-chevron">▼</div>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h3>The Problem Before Node.js</h3>
        <p>In the early 2000s, web servers handled requests one at a time. Every new user connection created a new thread. When thousands of users connected simultaneously, the server ran out of threads and crashed.</p>

        <div class="tips-grid">
          <div class="tip-card tip-bad">
            <div class="tip-header">❌ Before Node.js</div>
            <div class="tip-item">JavaScript only in browser</div>
            <div class="tip-item">Backend required Java / PHP / .NET</div>
            <div class="tip-item">Each request = 1 new thread</div>
            <div class="tip-item">Slow with many connections</div>
            <div class="tip-item">Teams needed two languages</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tip-card tip-good">
            <div class="tip-header">✅ After Node.js (2009)</div>
            <div class="tip-item">JavaScript runs everywhere</div>
            <div class="tip-item">Frontend + Backend = same language</div>
            <div class="tip-item">Handles thousands of connections</div>
            <div class="tip-item">Non-blocking (doesn't wait)</div>
            <div class="tip-item">One team handles full stack</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="diagram">
          <strong style="color:var(--text3); font-size:11px; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:.08em;">Before Node.js</strong><br><br>
          <div class="node">Frontend → JavaScript</div>
          <div class="node red-card" style="background:var(--red-dim); border-color:var(--red); color:var(--red)">Backend → Java / PHP / .NET</div>
          <br><br>
          <strong style="color:var(--text3); font-size:11px; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:.08em;">After Node.js</strong><br><br>
          <div class="node green">Frontend → JavaScript</div>
          <div class="node green">Backend → JavaScript ✓</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- S3: RUNTIME ENVIRONMENT -->
    <div class="section open" id="s3">
      <div class="section-head" onclick="toggle('s3')">
        <div class="section-num">03</div>
        <div class="section-title">What is a Runtime Environment?</div>
        <div class="section-chevron">▼</div>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h3>Compiler vs Interpreter vs Runtime</h3>
        <div class="card-grid">
          <div class="card green-card">
            <div class="card-icon">📝</div>
            <div class="card-title">Compiler</div>
            <div class="card-desc">Translates your entire code to machine language before running. Like translating a whole book before reading it. (Example: C, C++)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card purple-card">
            <div class="card-icon">📖</div>
            <div class="card-title">Interpreter</div>
            <div class="card-desc">Translates and runs your code line by line. Like reading a book and explaining it sentence by sentence. (Example: Python)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card yellow-card">
            <div class="card-icon">⚙️</div>
            <div class="card-title">Runtime Environment</div>
            <div class="card-desc">The full system where your code runs — includes the engine, memory, libraries, and OS access. Node.js IS a runtime environment.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="analogy">
          <div class="analogy-title">🎬 Analogy — Movie Production</div>
          <div class="analogy-body">
            <strong>Movie Script</strong> = Your JavaScript code<br>
            <strong>Director reading the script</strong> = JavaScript interpreter<br>
            <strong>Full Film Studio</strong> (cameras, lights, actors, sets) = Runtime Environment<br><br>
            Node.js provides the entire "film studio" for your JavaScript to run on the server.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="callout info">
          <div class="callout-icon">🔑</div>
          <div class="callout-text"><strong>Key point:</strong> Node.js is not a framework (like Express). It is the <em>runtime</em> — the foundational environment on which frameworks like Express are built.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- S4: V8 ENGINE -->
    <div class="section open" id="s4">
      <div class="section-head" onclick="toggle('s4')">
        <div class="section-num">04</div>
        <div class="section-title">Understanding the V8 Engine</div>
        <div class="section-chevron">▼</div>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h3>What is V8?</h3>
        <p>V8 is the <strong>JavaScript engine</strong> built by Google. It is written in C++ and is extremely fast. Chrome uses V8 to run JavaScript in the browser. Node.js <em>borrowed</em> V8 and wrapped it with server-side capabilities.</p>

        <div class="callout success">
          <div class="callout-icon">🚀</div>
          <div class="callout-text"><strong>Why is V8 so fast?</strong> V8 compiles JavaScript directly to native machine code instead of interpreting it step-by-step. This makes it 10–100x faster than older interpreters.</div>
        </div>

        <h3>How V8 Executes Your Code</h3>
        <div class="diagram">
          <div class="node">Your JavaScript Code</div>
          <div class="arrow">↓ parsing</div>
          <div class="node">Abstract Syntax Tree (AST)</div>
          <div class="arrow">↓ bytecode generation</div>
          <div class="node yellow">Ignition (Interpreter)</div>
          <div class="arrow">↓ hot code optimization</div>
          <div class="node green">TurboFan (JIT Compiler)</div>
          <div class="arrow">↓</div>
          <div class="node purple">Native Machine Code ⚡</div>
        </div>

        <div class="flow-steps">
          <div class="flow-step">
            <div class="flow-step-num">1</div>
            <div class="flow-step-content">
              <div class="flow-step-title">Parser reads your code</div>
              <div class="flow-step-desc">V8 reads your .js file character by character and checks for syntax errors</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="flow-step">
            <div class="flow-step-num">2</div>
            <div class="flow-step-content">
              <div class="flow-step-title">AST is created</div>
              <div class="flow-step-desc">Your code is converted to an Abstract Syntax Tree — a structured tree representation of your program</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="flow-step">
            <div class="flow-step-num">3</div>
            <div class="flow-step-content">
              <div class="flow-step-title">Ignition generates bytecode</div>
              <div class="flow-step-desc">The Ignition interpreter converts the AST to bytecode and starts executing immediately</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="flow-step">
            <div class="flow-step-num">4</div>
            <div class="flow-step-content">
              <div class="flow-step-title">TurboFan optimizes hot code</div>
              <div class="flow-step-desc">Code that runs many times gets JIT-compiled to super-fast native machine code by TurboFan</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- S5: BROWSER VS NODE -->
    <div class="section open" id="s5">
      <div class="section-head" onclick="toggle('s5')">
        <div class="section-num">05</div>
        <div class="section-title">Browser JavaScript vs Node.js — Key Differences</div>
        <div class="section-chevron">▼</div>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <p>Both use V8 to run JavaScript — but the environments around them are very different.</p>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Browser</th><th>Node.js</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>🖼 DOM (HTML manipulation)</td><td class="tag-yes">✅ Yes</td><td class="tag-no">❌ No</td></tr>
              <tr><td>🪟 window object</td><td class="tag-yes">✅ Yes</td><td class="tag-no">❌ No</td></tr>
              <tr><td>🌐 document object</td><td class="tag-yes">✅ Yes</td><td class="tag-no">❌ No</td></tr>
              <tr><td>📁 File System access</td><td class="tag-no">❌ No</td><td class="tag-yes">✅ Yes</td></tr>
              <tr><td>🔌 HTTP Servers</td><td class="tag-no">❌ No</td><td class="tag-yes">✅ Yes</td></tr>
              <tr><td>🗄 Database access</td><td class="tag-no">❌ No</td><td class="tag-yes">✅ Yes</td></tr>
              <tr><td>📦 NPM packages</td><td class="tag-no">❌ Limited</td><td class="tag-yes">✅ Full access</td></tr>
              <tr><td>🌍 Purpose</td><td>UI / Frontend</td><td>Server / Backend</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h3>Code That Works in Browser but FAILS in Node.js</h3>
        <div class="code-block">
          <div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">JavaScript (Browser only ❌ in Node.js)</span><span class="code-copy" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy</span></div>
          <pre><span class="cm">// This works in browser — but NOT in Node.js</span>
<span class="fn">console</span>.<span class="fn">log</span>(<span class="var">window</span>.<span class="var">innerWidth</span>);  <span class="cm">// ❌ ReferenceError: window is not defined</span>
<span class="var">document</span>.<span class="fn">getElementById</span>(<span class="str">'app'</span>);   <span class="cm">// ❌ ReferenceError: document is not defined</span></pre>
        </div>

        <h3>Code That Works in Node.js but NOT in Browser</h3>
        <div class="code-block">
          <div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">JavaScript (Node.js only ✅)</span><span class="code-copy" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy</span></div>
          <pre><span class="cm">// This works in Node.js — but NOT in browser</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> <span class="var">fs</span> = <span class="fn">require</span>(<span class="str">'fs'</span>);                       <span class="cm">// File system module</span>
<span class="var">fs</span>.<span class="fn">writeFileSync</span>(<span class="str">'hello.txt'</span>, <span class="str">'Hello World'</span>);  <span class="cm">// ✅ Creates a file</span>
<span class="fn">console</span>.<span class="fn">log</span>(<span class="var">process</span>.<span class="var">platform</span>);                  <span class="cm">// ✅ 'linux', 'win32', 'darwin'</span></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- S6: INSTALL -->
    <div class="section" id="s6">
