      <div class="section-body">
        <p style="margin-bottom:16px">Click each question to reveal the answer. These are frequently asked in Node.js interviews.</p>

        <div class="iq-item">
          <div class="iq-question" onclick="toggleIQ(this)">
            <span class="iq-q-num">Q1</span>
            What is Node.js? How is it different from a framework?
          </div>
          <div class="iq-answer">
            <div class="iq-answer-label">✅ Answer</div>
            Node.js is a <strong>JavaScript runtime environment</strong> built on Chrome's V8 engine. It allows JavaScript to run on the server side (outside the browser). A framework (like Express.js) is a structured library built ON TOP of Node.js that provides patterns for building web apps. Node.js is the foundation; Express.js is a house built on that foundation.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="iq-item">
          <div class="iq-question" onclick="toggleIQ(this)">
            <span class="iq-q-num">Q2</span>
            Why is Node.js fast?
          </div>
          <div class="iq-answer">
            <div class="iq-answer-label">✅ Answer</div>
            Node.js is fast for three reasons: (1) <strong>V8 engine</strong> compiles JavaScript to native machine code using JIT compilation; (2) <strong>Non-blocking I/O</strong> — it never waits for slow operations, so it handles many requests simultaneously; (3) <strong>Event-driven architecture</strong> — uses a single thread with an event loop, avoiding expensive thread creation and context switching.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="iq-item">
          <div class="iq-question" onclick="toggleIQ(this)">
            <span class="iq-q-num">Q3</span>
            Is Node.js single-threaded? Doesn't that make it slow?
          </div>
          <div class="iq-answer">
            <div class="iq-answer-label">✅ Answer</div>
            Yes, Node.js uses a <strong>single main thread</strong>, but this doesn't make it slow. Traditional servers create a new thread per request (expensive). Node.js uses one thread with an <strong>event loop</strong> and non-blocking I/O. While one request waits for a database response, the event loop handles other requests. This is very efficient for I/O-bound tasks. For CPU-heavy tasks, Node.js provides <code>Worker Threads</code> for actual multi-threading.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="iq-item">
          <div class="iq-question" onclick="toggleIQ(this)">
            <span class="iq-q-num">Q4</span>
            What is the V8 engine?
          </div>
          <div class="iq-answer">
            <div class="iq-answer-label">✅ Answer</div>
            V8 is Google's open-source JavaScript engine written in C++. It compiles JavaScript directly to native machine code using <strong>Just-In-Time (JIT) compilation</strong>. The process: Parser → AST → Ignition (interpreter/bytecode) → TurboFan (optimizing compiler) → Machine code. This makes JavaScript execution very fast. Node.js wraps V8 and adds server-side APIs (file system, network, etc.) on top.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="iq-item">
          <div class="iq-question" onclick="toggleIQ(this)">
            <span class="iq-q-num">Q5</span>
            What is the difference between Node.js and JavaScript?
          </div>
          <div class="iq-answer">
            <div class="iq-answer-label">✅ Answer</div>
            <strong>JavaScript</strong> is a programming language. <strong>Node.js</strong> is an environment that runs JavaScript. Think of JavaScript as a recipe and Node.js as the kitchen that executes the recipe. Without Node.js (or a browser), JavaScript is just text — it cannot run. Node.js adds server-side capabilities like file system access, networking, and process management that don't exist in browser JavaScript.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="iq-item">
          <div class="iq-question" onclick="toggleIQ(this)">
            <span class="iq-q-num">Q6</span>
            What is non-blocking I/O in Node.js?
          </div>
          <div class="iq-answer">
            <div class="iq-answer-label">✅ Answer</div>
            Non-blocking I/O means Node.js initiates an I/O operation (like reading a file or querying a database) and immediately moves on to handle other code, <strong>without waiting</strong> for that operation to complete. When the operation finishes, a callback (or Promise) is called. This allows a single thread to handle thousands of concurrent operations — unlike traditional blocking servers where each operation freezes the thread until completion.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="iq-item">
          <div class="iq-question" onclick="toggleIQ(this)">
            <span class="iq-q-num">Q7</span>
            Name 5 companies that use Node.js and why they chose it.
          </div>
          <div class="iq-answer">
            <div class="iq-answer-label">✅ Answer</div>
            <strong>Netflix</strong> — reduced startup time 70%, uses Node.js for UI layer. <strong>PayPal</strong> — 35% faster response time vs Java, same code team for frontend/backend. <strong>LinkedIn</strong> — reduced servers from 30 to 3 for their mobile backend. <strong>Walmart</strong> — zero downtime during Black Friday with 500M+ requests. <strong>Uber</strong> — real-time driver/rider matching at massive scale using WebSockets.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="iq-item">
          <div class="iq-question" onclick="toggleIQ(this)">
            <span class="iq-q-num">Q8</span>
            What are the limitations of Node.js?
          </div>
          <div class="iq-answer">
            <div class="iq-answer-label">✅ Answer</div>
            Key limitations: (1) <strong>Not ideal for CPU-intensive tasks</strong> — heavy computation blocks the single event loop thread. (2) <strong>Callback complexity</strong> — heavy use of callbacks led to "callback hell" (mitigated by Promises/async-await). (3) <strong>Immature for heavy ML/AI</strong> — Python is better suited. (4) <strong>Rapid API changes</strong> — some core APIs changed between versions. Solutions: Worker Threads for CPU tasks, async/await for callback hell.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="iq-item">
          <div class="iq-question" onclick="toggleIQ(this)">
            <span class="iq-q-num">Q9</span>
            What is the difference between require() and import in Node.js?
          </div>
          <div class="iq-answer">
            <div class="iq-answer-label">✅ Answer</div>
            <code>require()</code> is CommonJS (the original Node.js module system) — synchronous, loaded at runtime, can be called anywhere in code. <code>import</code> is ES Modules (ES6) — asynchronous, statically analyzed at parse time, must be at the top level. Modern Node.js supports both. Most older codebases use CommonJS (<code>require</code>); newer projects prefer ES Modules (<code>import/export</code>). You set <code>"type": "module"</code> in package.json to use ESM.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="iq-item">
          <div class="iq-question" onclick="toggleIQ(this)">
            <span class="iq-q-num">Q10</span>
            What is process in Node.js?
          </div>
          <div class="iq-answer">
            <div class="iq-answer-label">✅ Answer</div>
            <code>process</code> is a global Node.js object — no need to require it. It provides information and control over the current Node.js process. Key properties: <code>process.version</code> (Node version), <code>process.platform</code> (OS), <code>process.env</code> (environment variables), <code>process.argv</code> (command-line arguments), <code>process.exit()</code> (terminate the process), <code>process.cwd()</code> (current working directory). It does NOT exist in browser JavaScript.
          </div>
        </div>

